<mxCell id="C_A75j5agU9bFt2IBsdl-218" value="<ol style="line-height: 170%;"><li>Coin change flow diagram: Target amount = 7, denominations are 1, 3, and 4.</li><li>The target amount is attempted with each coin, and the result of each operation is further attempted with each coin. It represents an outer loop for the target amount and an inner loop for the coins.</li><li>We observe 2 shortest paths (7 -&gt; 4 -&gt; 0 and 7 -&gt; 3 -&gt; 0) and 1 longest path (7 -&gt; 6 -&gt; 5 -&gt; 4 -&gt; 3 -&gt; 2 -&gt; 1 -&gt; 0).</li><li>We also notice that we can reduce repetitive calculations (e.g., when the target amount is 4, 3, 2, or 1) by using memoization (cache).</li></ol>" ol.li: Coin change flow diagram: Target amount = 7, denominations are 1, 3, and 4.

The target amount is attempted with each coin, and the result of each operation is further attempted with each coin. This process continues as long as the target amount is greater than the coin, until the target amount becomes 0. It represents an outer loop for the target amount and an inner loop for the coins.
We observe 2 shortest paths (7 -> 4 -> 0 and 7 -> 3 -> 0) and 1 longest path (7 -> 6 -> 5 -> 4 -> 3 -> 2 -> 1 -> 0).
We also notice that we can reduce repetitive calculations (e.g., when the target amount is 4, 3, 2, or 1) by using memoization (cache).
